description:
## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
complexity
## Location
src/tools/bash/kill.rs:38-53
## Violation
After SIGTERM the code polls process existence by spawning `kill -0 <pid>` every 50ms for up to 2 seconds — that's up to 40 fork/exec cycles per kill, plus the 50ms sleep granularity. Each subprocess walks PATH, allocates a Process, runs a syscall, then exits. The cost is paid even when the child exits immediately.

Quoted (kill.rs:38-53):
```
        let deadline = Instant::now() + Duration::from_secs(2);
        let mut exited = false;
        while Instant::now() < deadline {
            let check = Command::new("kill").args(["-0", &pid_str]).output();
            match check {
                Ok(output) if !output.status.success() => {
                    exited = true;
                    break;
                }
                _ => {
                    std::thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(50));
                }
            }
        }
```
## Mandated refactor
1. Use `nix::sys::wait::waitpid(pid, Some(WaitPidFlag::WNOHANG))` with `nix::sys::signal::kill(pid, None)` (libc — zero subprocesses).
2. Or use a `crossbeam_channel::after(Duration)` + a channel populated by the existing wait thread so the kill path just blocks on a signal rather than polling.
